@Dolby 109 Go ahead and list each car's stock tire type and size then! A car can be sold with different stock tires (different brands, different models or option packs can have very different stickier tires, etc.) and different tire sizes. Cars supplied to track tests are DEFINITELY NOT supplied on only certain tires for each car brand and model! 

You are absolutely, positively, very very wrong in thinking that 'most of them are on Cup 2's'. 

A performance test needs to disclose the exact tires used on each car for it to have any value whatsoever. There is also no reason to withhold that info. Frankly, there should be lots of other info supplied as well, like for example German track testers Sport Auto does.Ôªø

@5putput
¬†I agree there would be value added if tire information was supplied (like it might be in the magazine article) but thats a long stretch from saying without that info the tests don't hold value.
All of these cars are supposed to be on factory (optional) rubber.¬† If you bother looking it up, several of these cars have optional Pilot Sport Cup 2 tires (off the top of my head the Mustang, M4, Audi, and 911, and more).Ôªø

@5putput You don't understand how factory options are still considered stock? You know the 1LE package is an option for the Camaro (basically the same with EVERY CAR HERE).
Additionally many of them allow you to spec for better tires from the factory.

Anyway I already agreed that MT should have provided the tire info.¬† Not knowing what they are doesn't change that they are all still "STOCK TIRES".Ôªø

@Dolby 109 If you ask a car manufacturers as to what 'stock tires' it'll come with, they will say that there is no such thing, they cannot guarantee the delivery with any specific brand or type of tire.

Manufacturers have supplied cars to track tests with all kinds of tires. You can of course go over dozens and dozens of track tests in detail, and then attempt to prove me wrong.

Jesus, just let it go. There is no such thing as 'stock tires', only a few cars models' special versions or a few with optional packs will be delivered on specific brand and types of tires. And there is no sense in dumbing down this issue with attempting to create some stupid term like 'stock tires', especially as it helps no-one in no way in knowing what F'ing tires are on the tested cars!!!Ôªø

